         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">20/10/81. ¶  ¶ I write a sort of duplicate letter, dear Sir Joseph, concerning poor Dr Cooke. ¶  ¶ As a medical Gentleman you will know, what the end of his sufferings will be, unless he has a long &amp; ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">81.10.20</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller. 1871-81, ff. 336-7.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">20/10/81.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I write a sort of duplicate letter, dear Sir Joseph, concerning poor Dr Cooke.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mordecai Cooke; see M to J. Hooker, 8 October 1881.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As a medical Gentleman you will know, what the end of his sufferings will be, unless he has a long &amp; total change from Museum work to openair-occupation. Sadly do I feel this daily myself, after I had to quit my garden! Unless, as in the instance of Dr Cooke, the recuperative power of the system of a man, already beyond the zenith of his life, is brought into full play, his chances for resumation of long &amp; trying work in the Museum will be very poor. If however you could manage, to send him to Central-America, not to the lowland-jungles, but to the healthy upland-country, he would do wonders for Mycology, and get simultaneously his system thoroughly invigorated. Remember, that this would be the first instance of a special Mycologist working outside of Europe!</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Through Berkeley you have probably already the largest collection of fungs at Kew, unless Fries’s collection should be larger; how much would that be increased at Kew, by a few months wanderings of Dr Cooke in the tropics.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In a single Census of Australian genera, now under print,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B82.13.08.</p>
               </note> I have placed <name key="Antennaria%20nubigena">Antennaria nubigena</name> under Leontopodium. You seem to have seen only its one state; it is dimorphic, &amp; thus bridges over the chasm between Antennaria &amp; Leontopodium, especially as DC's <name key="Antennaria%20leontopodina">Antennaria leontopodina</name>, gathered by Royle, yourself &amp; Turczaninow, is only a form of <name key="Leontopodium%20alpinum">Leontopodium alpinum</name>. I am just looking over the New Zealand <name key="Raoulia">Raoulia</name>s to see, whether any can be transferred like wise to Leontopodium or (if you prefer) Antennaria.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See B82.13.12, where M discusses the history of the systematics of the species.</p>
               </note> I wrote on this subject to Prof. Asa Gray some years ago.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M to A. Gray, 18 October 1858 (in this edition as 58-10-18a).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am trying to get an other stem of <name key="Macrozamia%20Moorei">Macrozamia Moorei</name> to Kew, to ensure the growth there of this superb plant.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">How glad I am, that the sad tidings concerning Bentham from Planchon and Caruell are not confirmed.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to J. Hooker, 19 September 1881 (in this edition as 81-09-19a) and J. Hooker to M, 9 November 1881.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am reminded how the elder Agassiz's life was prolonged by his voyages up the Amazon River. He wrote to me himself then;<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found.</p>
               </note> he had many fishes from me.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>We have here now a branch of the British Medical Association, and this I have joined.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Kindly help me by giving me a clue of any recent writings on Polynesian plants.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to J. Hooker, 7 October 1881, and notes thereto.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Antennaria%20leontopodina">Antennaria leontopodina</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Antennaria%20nubigena">Antennaria nubigena</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Leontopodium%20alpinum">Leontopodium alpinum</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Macrozamia%20Moorei">Macrozamia Moorei</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Raoulia">Raoulia</name>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
